msIdentifier.repository: Pembroke College Library: on long-term deposit at Cambridge University Library

msDesc.head: Matthew, glossed; Anselm of Laon, Commentary on Matthew

note.p: The following additions were written in the same hand as f. i recto and the main texts:
Folio i recto: the end of a commentary on the Lord's Prayer: 'Si septem dona Sancti Spiritus habere desideras ... post seculi laborem possideamus in s. s. amen' (12th-century) (Bloomfield 5602).

Folio ii recto: interpretations of Old Testament names and figures. Folio ii verso-iii verso: glosses on Matthew's genealogy, Liber generationis (as in Pembroke MS 67, ff. 1r-2v), divided into paragraphs, each with an initial in the same ink as the text, highlighted in yellow, sometimes with brown pen-work ornament:
Prefatione tocius operis premisit de quo dicturus erat
Spiritualiter per hos patriarcas ad nostram salutem Christus ueniens in mundum
Moraliter hee quoque interpretaciones nominum
Cum multi scripsisse euangelia legantur
Matheus in hac uita que quatuor temporum cursu labitur
Mateus sicut in ordine ponitur euangelium in iudea (Stegmüller 590)
Tres tesserescedecades in generatione Christi
Sicut per xlii. mansiones peruenerunt carnales Israelite
Folio i recto: beneath the 12th-century addition, a fragment of gloss and notes in 13th-century anglicana script.
Folios 128r-129r: miscellaneous notes, extracts on simony, against women, etc.

binding.p: Late medieval half-binding of tawed skin over flush, cushion-bevelled oak boards; sewn on five bands, raised on the rounded spine. The rear board is reused from the earlier binding, which was sewn on two bands. Two marks of chain-staples at the top of the front board. Formerly a strap from a recess in the front board to a pin at the rear. Folio i was originally the front pastedown, and f. 132 was originally the rear pastedown. Folio iv is a later insertion (the recto of which is blank). Retrimmed, affecting the gloss in the outer margin of ff. 1-70 and the marginal auctoritates on ff. 71-127.

history.origin:
Second quarter of the 12th century. Northern France, ?Laon.
The manuscript was made in northern France, perhaps at Laon, and was at the Abbey of Bury St Edmunds Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds from an early stage. The manuscript comprises two physically separate volumes, which appear always to have been together.
CBMLC 4, B13.130

provenance.p: Pressmark (B.97), written by the hand of Henry Kirkestede (c. 1314-c. 1379) Kirkestede, Henry, approximately 1314-approximately 1378 (f. i recto).
Title, the abbey's ex libris and press-mark, in the usual large formal textura of the 15th century (f. iv verso).

history.acquisition: Presumably given to Pembroke College, Cambridge Pembroke College in 1599 by William Smart (d. 1599) Smart, William, portreeve of Ipswich, -1599 , though it is not recorded by Thomas James or Matthew Wren. It was certainly at Pembroke by 1600: Thomas James's number 249 is written at the head of f. 1r. The College bookplate is pasted onto f. i verso.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by Rodney M. Thomson, A descriptive catalogue of the medieval manuscripts at Pembroke College, Cambridge (2022) (used here by kind permission of the author).

availability.p: Researchers should note that Pembroke College's western European medieval manuscripts are housed at Cambridge University Library (CUL). Scholars who wish to consult Pembroke College manuscripts should contact the Manuscripts Reading Room at CUL to arrange their visit; all CUL admissions procedures will apply. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library. For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

seg.seg: Text: in the second of three columns, in the middle of the page, frame and lines ruled in hardpoint, of consistent width of 55mm. 11-22 lines, written above top line, in larger script.
Gloss: Ruled in two columns in hardpoint on either side of the text column, of consistent width of 30mm and 55mm. Lines ruled for the gloss on an apparently ad hoc basis, or not at all.

handNote.p: Text written by a single French scribe in protogothic bookhand. This appears to be a larger version of the gloss, which was written by the same scribe, as well as others, and which also appears in Part 2 and on ff. i recto-iii verso and 128r-129v.

decoNote.p: The opening word of the Gospel (Liber) is written in red capitals (f. 1r). Elsewhere, in the text, are small red initials, for a while highlighted in yellow, a few larger with ornament, one with green.
